'''William McAlpine''' (3 December, 1922 <U+2013> 2 February 2004) was leading British [[tenor]] during the 1950s and 60s. He created roles in two operas by [[Benjamin Britten]]<U+2014> A Novice in ''[[Billy Budd (opera)|Billy Budd]]'' and The Spirit of the Masque in ''[[Gloriana]]''. He also sang Andres in the UK premiere of [[Alban Berg|Berg]]'s ''[[Wozzeck]]''.

McAlpine was born in [[Stenhousemuir]], Scotland and initially worked as bricklayer before studying at the [[Guildhall School of Music]]. He made his stage debut in 1951 as  the third Jew in a revival of [[Richard Strauss]]'s ''[[Salome (opera)|Salome]]'' at the [[Royal Opera House]], and went on to sing several there and at the [[Sadlers Wells]] company, which he joined in 1956 as a principal tenor. He later sang with the [[Scottish Opera]] and [[Glyndebourne Festival Opera]] as well as in Berlin, Prague, and Paris. After his retirement from the stage, he taught singing at the Guildhall School of Music. He died in [[Surrey]] at the age of 81 following a heart attack after one of his teaching sessions at Guildhall.<ref>[[Alan Blyth|Blyth, Alan]] (13 February 2004). [http://www.theguardian.com/news/2004/feb/13/guardianobituaries.artsobituaries "William McAlpine, Leading British tenor who found his voice on a building site"]. ''[[The Guardian]]''. Retrieved 28 October 2013.</ref><ref>''[[The Scotsman]]'' (10 February 2004). [http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/william-mcalpine-1-513210 "William McAlpine"]. Retrieved 28 October 2013.</ref>

